		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> No future for Moria ??<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.69)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12956'>Jean Paul "HB" Agez</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12956&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 21, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> First, I will look at why people think Moria is dead, and explain why I dont think so...<br />
<br />
First and foremost, people cite the Balrog. No more Balrog means Moria isnt guaranteed a big hit at site 5. But, in the last tournament you played in, what was the damage done by the Balrog? A dead Pippen and Sam? A couple wounds on an Armored Boromir? A Stealth and a Filibert ? Honestly, the Balrog doesnt do a whole lot nowadays to a fellowship that hasnt already been picked apart. Everyone knows how to survive it, and the cards that stop him are all very strong against other popular strategies. Will the loss of the Balrog hurt Moria in the new set? Of course. Will it kill it? No way. <br />
<br />
Next people say, &quot;But there&#39;s no new Moria cards in the new set&quot;. Well thats true (as for Rotel, in fact), but its not like Moria doesnt have a strong foundation to build from . What is missing for Moria ? What new cards could they possibly ask for? Maybe some more versitile condition removal, or the ability to bring back conditions, but beyond that, they are already stacked. Furthermore, there were no cards in the new set to really counter Moria. The only cards I can think of is Mithrandir, Mithrandir! and Wizardry indeed but I doubt Mithrandir, Mithrandir! will even make an impact. Why not? What is effected by this card? Moria and maybe the Easterlings? Well in Moria, the runner is the only popularly used minion that will die from it, the scout will take a wound, and thats assuming the runner doesnt get a Scimitar placed on it. Wizardry Indeed is another card that might see some success against Moria. But, the shadow player chooses what minion goes away. Granted, it can save you at a site, but it cant get you all the way to 9. None of the rest of the cards really work against Moria. <br />
<br />
But what about the new Fellowship cultures? Well, they really don&#39;t effect Moria. The two big ones being Gondor and Rohan, neither of their abilities really effect Moria in the slightest.<br />
<br />
Lets take Gondor first. Making Minions roaming during the skirmish phase only effects ring-bound men, and Frodo is not a ring-bound man. Since Moria is a swarming shadow, its whole goal is to get a couple of minions on Frodo, and the new Gondor men can&#39;t do anything about that. They can all use Elendil&#39;s Valor to get a lot of Defender+1 or Maybe Heir of Elendil in the new Trust Deck, but that&#39;s not really a new defense. But what about the +2 strength vs roaming minions? Well, Faramir with Sword, Brand, and a fully charged last alliance, vs a Roaming cave Troll is strength 15. That means he still loses the skirmish. Or he could exert 4 times with his bow to kill the Cave Troll. What about pumps? Well, pumps have always been there and have never hurt me too bad before, so why would it start now? And what about my goblins? Well, I am pretty used to my goblins losing all their skirmishes, anyway. <br />
<br />
On to Rohan. Rohan&#39;s big mechanic is the Minion Exertion  at the start of the skirmish phase. Well, what does that do to Moria? Not a whole lot. The scout and Troll have to exert, and thats not a bit deal. Lets take Eomer with Firefoot and his Spear vs an Exausted Cave Troll. Eomer is Strength 15. Again, Cave Troll wins the skirmish. Theoden&#39;s Hearken To Me is pretty useless against Moria swarm. It does nothing to protect the Ring Bearer. Eowyn again has a great ability, but it wont stop a swarm. Over all, Rohan brings nothing new to the table to combat swarms. <br />
<br />
Just for kicks I will touch the Elf and Dwarf cultures for a second. <br />
<br />
Elves seem to have taken a hit in archery. That was their only real defense against swarms. Most part of their new stuff seems to be focused towards drawing cards, liberation and winning skirmishes, none of which help a great deal agaisnt a good swarm; But there is one threat in the new cards that will be pretty strong against moria : Company of archers which destroys armories in archery phase.<br />
<br />
Dwarves boast a good deal of new conditions and many of them are pretty good, but Moria is already tipped agaisnt Dwarves. The Goblin Warrior wrecks all the new condtion fun. Beyond that, the dwarves appear to have a lot of emphisis on pumping and getting Damage+1. Not too helpful against swarms. But there is a card that will be hard to deal with : Quick as may be !<br />
<br />
The Shire is the only culture that has many useful cards vs swarms. First, Frodo&#39;s Cloak is a great card and very effective against swarms, but its only as good as Intuition. After site 4, theres little practical application for this card against Swarms, and 5-8 is the usual kill zone for Moria, anyway. The new Intuition is the best card vs swarm since it cancels and then Bounders. The bounder effect is great, but there was bounder in Fellowship, and he wasnt enough to kill Moria, so this card wont either. If it becomes a problem, Relentlessness will follow. <br />
<br />
In conclusion, the new options offer by TTT will not be too dangerous for a good Moria swarm Deck,if we consider that fellowship side will give more twilight than before...<br />
<br />
Then people say, &quot;Look at all the new Shadows, why on earth would you want to play stinky old Moria?&quot; Well, simple, Moria is still the best cycling culture and the best Swarming culture. It is the only shadow that can put 5 minions down for 4 twilight (except maybe the Easterlings with that new Skirmisher). Many fellowships will be focusing on beating the new shadows. This means Moria swarm, early on, will be forgotten. That is when Moria is especially dangerous. Decks that dont have anything to combat swarms tend to lose to Moria. Now if Dunlands or the Raiders had brought a better cycling engine to the table, I would be all for that, but Moria is still the place to go to move through your deck fast. <br />
<br />
&quot;But Moria lost all of its powerful Sites.&quot; <br />
True, Dimril Dale, Mithril Mine, Anduin Wilderlands and the Shores of Nen Hithoel helped make Moria the powerhouse that it was. But, at the same time, The Great River and Caras Galadhon were very bad when they hit the table. The loss of some key sites hurts Moria, but at the same time the new sites are neutral. Theres no new sites that really help and there are no new sites that really hinder Moria. It is nice to see 2 late game Underground sites, though. This will help the people who found it hard to get that Troll out at site 7 to stop their opponent. <br />
<br />
But so what if it cycles and so what if it swarms, how can it win you games? Well, I have always liked my Moria deck paired with a strong, fast moving fellowship. Moria helps get the cards the fellowship needs to move and the fellowship helps make the opponent double for Moria. If paired up with a strong Gondor or Big Fellowship deck, Moria will shine in the new set. A Gondor deck, starting Faramir and Ranger of Ithilien, can bid 5, go first and double the whole way to 9. Moria cycles through the cards and gets the rangers what they need to keep running. In turn, the fact that the rangers are moving so fast means your opponent has to double to keep up. That gives Moria the time to set up a kill. <br />
<br />
Moria has many lightly tapped resources (at least in my area they are lightly tapped). If you are still upset about the Balrog, add the Cave Trolls Hammer. It gets the Troll to 18/4 Damage+2, which is bigger than the Balrog, and  its available at every site, can be used multiple times with a Relics of Moria AND with armories out (and/or Trolls Keyward), can cost less than the Balrog from the get go. If you want stopping power, use the big orcs like the Patrol Troop. That can help make up for the loss of the Balrog. There are plenty of cool options that Moria still has available.<br />
<br />
Even if you think that&#39;s not according to the story, you can based your shadow on a mix between Dunland and Moria with Hides and Armories to prevent your minion from beeing shoot like rabbits, then you can add a few War clubs  or play Dunlending Pillager to remove a few items like Bow(Aragorn&#39;s or Galadhrim) or Sting &Co.<br />
<br />
Finally, do you still think Moria is dead ?<br />
 <br />
